-- Asian Stocks Post Weekly Advance on Company Earnings Optimism
-- B y   A n n a   K i t a n a k a
-- 2013-11-02T00:02:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-02/asian-stocks-post-weekly-advance-on-company-earnings-optimism.html
Asian  stocks  ended the week little
changed as investors weighed optimism about corporate earnings
against concern the  Federal Reserve  may start paring stimulus,
and as the dollar gained against Asian currencies.  Panasonic Corp. jumped 13 percent this week as the maker of
Viera televisions doubled its net-income forecast. Australia &
New Zealand Banking Group Ltd., the country’s third-largest
lender by market value, climbed 3.3 percent after posting a 13
percent rise in second-half cash profit.  State Bank of India 
soared 9.2 percent after the central bank took steps to boost
cash supply for lenders while raising key borrowing costs.
GungHo Online Entertainment Inc. tumbled 24 percent after
reporting profit fell.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index dipped less than 0.1 percent to
141.24 this week amid the busiest part of the earnings season
for shares on the measure. The Fed maintained its stimulus plan
while publishing a policy statement that economists at Citigroup
Inc. and Barclays Plc said opens the possibility of reduced bond
purchases as soon as December. The Asia Dollar Index fell 0.4
percent as the rupiah,  yuan , ringgit and rupee all retreated
from a week earlier.  “It’s becoming more and more obvious which companies are
strong, and which are weak,” said Seiichiro Iwamoto, who helps
oversee the equivalent of $33 billion at Mizuho Asset Management
Co. “We usually see cyclical weakness for the global economy
from around now through February, so I think we’re seeing the
best for corporate earnings being reported now.”  Japan ’s  Topix (TPX)  index added 0.4 percent this week.
Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index advanced 0.5 percent.  Singapore ’s
Straits Times Index slipped 0.1 percent.  Hong Kong, China  Hong Kong ’s Hang Seng Index gained 2.4 percent and  China ’s
Shanghai Composite climbed 0.8 percent as a report showed
China’s manufacturing exceeded estimates.  South Korea ’s Kospi
Index rose 0.3 percent.  Taiwan’s  Taiex Index  pared this week’s gain to 0.5 percent
after an earthquake measuring 6.3 on the Richter scale shook
buildings in the capital and prompted the island’s biggest
chipmaker to temporarily evacuate factory workers.  More than 300 companies on the MSCI Asia Pacific Index
reported  earnings  this week. Of those announcing quarterly
results this season and for which Bloomberg compiles  estimates ,
half posted profit that beat expectations while 53 percent
exceeded sales estimates, the data show.  Earnings  Panasonic jumped 13 percent to 1,046 yen in  Tokyo , its
highest since April 2011, after doubling its net income forecast
to 100 billion yen ($1 billion). Sales will rise to 7.4 trillion
yen, the company projected.  Keyence Corp. surged 19 percent to 41,550 yen, the second-biggest increase on the MSCI Asia Pacific Index, after reporting
that its first-half earnings surged.  Australia  & New Zealand Banking Group advanced 3.3 percent
to A$33.72 in Sydney and touched a record on Oct. 31 after
saying cash profit climbed to A$3.3 billion ($3.2 billion) in
the six months ended Sept. 30 from A$2.9 billion a year earlier.  Still, earnings at some companies disappointed investors.
Sony Corp. plunged 9.9 percent to 1,668 yen after unexpectedly
lowering its full-year profit forecast by 40 percent, on
stalling demand for TVs and digital cameras and box office
flops.  GungHo slumped 24 percent to 60,400 yen, the  biggest drop 
on the MSCI Asia Pacific index. The company’s third-quarter net
income fell to 14.4 billion yen from 15.9 billion yen the
previous quarter, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  State Bank  of  India  surged 9.2 percent to 1,879.00 rupees.  ICICI Bank Ltd. jumped 11 percent.  India Rates  Reserve Bank  of India Governor Raghuram Rajan cut the
marginal standing facility rate to 8.75 percent from 9 percent,
making short-term funds cheaper for banks. The cost was raised
in July in an emergency move to stem a drop in the currency.
Rajan, who pledged to contain price increases after taking
charge of the RBI last month, also raised the repurchase rate by
25 basis points to 7.75 percent on Oct. 29, as 32 of 42 analysts
in a Bloomberg News survey predicted.  The Standard & Poor’s 500 Index climbed 0.1 percent this
week. The Fed maintained $85 billion in monthly bond purchases,
saying that while the economy shows signs of “underlying
strength” it needs to see more evidence of sustainable
improvement.  The odds of a taper in January rose to 45 percent, from 25
percent before the decision, according to Citigroup. Economists
surveyed by Bloomberg Oct. 17-18 had predicted the Fed would
begin paring stimulus in March.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index gained 2.7 percent in October
for a second monthly increase. That pushed its  price-earnings 
ratio to 13.6 times estimated earnings yesterday from 12.7 at
the end of August, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. That
compares with multiples of 15.9 for the  Standard & Poor’s 500
Index (SPX)  and 14.9 for the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.  To contact the reporter on this story:
